<h2>How does the GreenCoin calculation work?</h2>
<p>GreenCoin is ultimately a measure of sequestered carbon AND carbon that is not produced during the production of renewable energy compared to the same amount of energy produced by the aggregate global average for the exact same activity. Therefore, it is closely tied with the amount of CO2 offset that can be calculated as a consequence of utilizing renewable energy versus non-renewable energy, as an example that is related to energy production. The current global average amount of CO2 emitted to produce 1kWh is about 527 g CO2. If a solar producer pushes 10 kWh to the grid, they’ve created power to the benefit of the grid users without the creation of 5.27 kg of CO2 entering the atmosphere (0.527 kg/kWh X 10 kWh = 5.27 kg).  This figure has been termed Carbon-Productivity Sequestration and the units are in kg CO2.  Carbon-Productivity Sequestration differs from carbon sequestration in that we reward the productive event (such as renewable power production) as opposed to penalizing the emissions. This provides for a mechanism to reward economic productivity for green commerce providers as opposed to financially limiting high-emitting ones.
 
The GreenCoin Foundation receives exactly one-half (50%) of all of the coins being mined via the traditional cryptocurrency mining method.  We have termed this as the compulsory sharing element.  The foundation aggregates the data of the producers who have effectuated carbon-productivity sequestration for that day.  We then distribute the coins received (currently about 1,350,000 per day) pro rata to all of the producers within the network.
 
